Macedonians hold a referendum to decide if they will change the name of the country
Last Sunday, the Macedonian people held a referendum on the change of name to the "Northern Republic of Macedonia", a measure that would resolve a dispute that had existed for decades with Greece, which had blocked Macedonia's applications for membership of the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, maintains that the name of its northern neighbor constitutes a claim of its territory and has banned it from entering NATO and the EU.
In June, the two governments reached an agreement on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change would undermine the ethnic identity of the majority Slavic population of Macedonia.
President Gjorge Ivanov has said he will not take part in the referendum, and a boycott campaign casts doubt as to whether it will reach the minimum required participation of 50% for the referendum to be valid.
The question indicated in the referendum paper is: “Are you in favor of joining NATO and the EU, with the acceptance of the agreement with Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a price worth paying to achieve Macedonia's accession, one of the countries that was created after the disintegration of Yugoslavia, to organizations such as the EU and NATO.
“Today I have come to vote for the future of the country, so that the young people of Macedonia can live freely in the European Union, because it means that we will all have a safer life,” said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, a sufficient number of parliamentarians have indicated that they will adhere to the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
To change the name, a two-thirds majority is required in Parliament.
The State Electoral Commission reported that there had been no irregularities at 1 p.m.
However, the turnout was only 16%, compared with 34% recorded in the last parliamentary elections, held in 2016, in which 66% of registered people voted.
“I’ve come to vote for my children, our place is in Europe,” Gjose Tanevski, 62, told reporters in Skopje.
Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted in the referendum held in Macedonia on the country's name change, which would open the way for him to join the European Union and NATO in Strumica, Macedonia, on September 30, 2018.
In front of the Parliament of Skopje, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov was preparing a small stage and placing chairs in front of the tents installed by the people boycotting the referendum.
“We are in favor of NATO and the EU, but we want to join with our heads high, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If they don’t want to accept us as Macedonia, we can go to other countries, such as China and Russia, and be part of Euro-Asian integration.”
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will be accompanied by more than necessary investments in Macedonia, which has a stopover rate of more than 20%.
“I think the vast majority will vote for it, because more than 80% of the citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO,” Zaev said before filing his paper.
Zaev declared that a “yes” would be the “confirmation of our future.”
In a poll published last Monday by the Macedonian Political Research Institute, between 30% and 43% of voters would participate in the referendum, a figure below the minimum necessary participation.
According to the results of another poll, conducted by Macedonian TV channel Telma TV, 57% of the respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70% said they would vote “yes.”
For the referendum to be valid, the turnout must be 50% plus one vote.
A failure in the referendum would be the first time the pro-Western government's policy has failed since it took office in May last year.
