John Edward: Linguistic competences are essential for the world’s citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a trajectory of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is reinforced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students from around Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer a service of the best level to students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, for the career they choose and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages remain a very popular and desired topic of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you’ll get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will come to his heart.”
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to establish relationships and generate trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of the current examinations, we can see that the languages lead the ranking tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages got the A-higher grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, reflected that 72% of students obtained a higher A qualification in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Currently, languages, as a subject of choice, are maintained in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans from independent schools and elsewhere.
A survey conducted in 2014 by the UK’s Commission on Occupation and Competence revealed that for the reasons that entrepreneurs gave to the fact that they were costing them to cover vacancies, 17% was attributed to the lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
Since there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the race a person chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future with a permanent competition like this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person in front of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and French, with 15% of speakers, was the only language with a double-digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowing different languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find an important job.
In Scotland, there is diversity among schools in the languages they are taught.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the UK in the future, by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, you can always choose from a number of languages in independent schools, which have specialist teaching staff in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
In today’s global trading environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be of vital importance to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be considered “international communicative competences”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
