North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm “in any way” unless signs of trust are appreciated
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying its distrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual General Assembly of the world body that North Korea had taken "significant goodwill measures" during the previous year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear testing center and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
“However, we do not observe any response in consonance with the United States,” he said.
“Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will not unilaterally initiate disarmament in any way.”
Although Ri resumed North Korea’s well-known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization approach by which North Korea would be rewarded as it gradually took action, his statements seemed significant in the fact that he did not reject the denuclearization as a single, plebiscite.
Ri made reference to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S.-led president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised assurances of North Korea’s security.
North Korea has attempted to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has announced that Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted the call to relax the harsh international sanctions imposed on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists that denuclearization must first occur and increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, as well as oppose the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a chimera of people who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that continued sanctions are intensifying our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If the part involved in the issue of denuclearization was South Korea instead of the U.S., the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula is not on the Coke Peninsula.
However, the tone of Ri’s speech was very different from what it held last year, when he told the UN General Assembly that targeting North Korean missiles on U.S. territory was inevitable after President “Mr. Evil” Trump dubbed Kim “Rocket Man in a Missile.”
Meanwhile at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take disarmament measures, but said there was still much to do and sanctions had to be maintained until North Korea denuclearized.
Last Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this and that “it doesn’t matter if it takes two years, three years or five months.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that “the implementation of sanctions by the Security Council must continue energetically and without exception until we confirm total and definitive denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously pushed sanctions on North Korea since 2006 in a bid to cut funding for Pyongyang’s ballistic and nuclear missile programs.
