Harvard students take a course on rest habits.
Now, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the ever-expanding culture of studying all night, stimulated by caffeine.
An academic noted that often students from the world's number-one university are disappointed with the basic aspects of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after making a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me now, all this, in my last year?’
He said that no one had ever told him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, students are explained the basic concepts about how good habits of sound improve academic and sports performance, in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the University's health services, said the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffer from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a bedroom, where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, bamboos and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, how it affects sports performance in lack of sleep, and the importance of maintaining a sleep routine.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of suffering from heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
Next, a campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily route.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride of staying up all night still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and the growing pressure that students suffer make sleep deprivation an ever-increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy a good quality sleep for a long time should be a “secret weapon” for students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, he added, even to avoid gaining weight, since the deprivation of sleep puts the brain in a state of inattention and makes them always study.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies Chemistry and Physical Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask graduate students to undertake a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact that they set an alarm when going to sleep and when they wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" that emit the electronic displays and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the sound of the rhyme.
