HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people affected in the country, according to health officials.
In the second quarter of 2018, 40,000 new cases were reported.
The vast majority of new cases are of sexual transmission, unlike what used to happen.
Traditionally, HIV was rapidly spreading in some regions of China due to infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people contracting HIV for this cause has been reduced to almost zero, according to Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan province.
Year after year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased 100,000 people.
Sexual transmission of HIV is a serious problem for the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT community is commonplace.
Taking into account the conservative values of the country, studies estimate that between 70 and 90% of men who maintain homosexual relationships end up marrying a woman.
Many of the transmissions of diseases are due to the lack of adequate precautions in sexual relations.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to address the problem.
