How the U.S.-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The initial rescues from the U.S.-China trade war were deafening and, although it does not appear that the war should end soon, a distancing of countries may prove beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued his first warning earlier this year, when he imposed taxes on China’s major exports, such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation occurred this week, with new arrangements affecting $200 billion worth of products. These arrangements entail a tax on half of all goods arriving in the U.S. from China.
Beijing has repeatedly counterattacked in the same way and has recently raised the tariffs from five to ten percent for US$60 billion in goods.
China has committed to replicating the U.S. and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will be back in the near future.
Making Washington do it back involves giving in to some demands, but leaning publicly in front of the U.S. would be too shameful for Xi Jinping, the President of China.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards well, the pressures of the trade war with the US could benefit China in the long term by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick political decision in Washington or Beijing could create the conditions that would trigger a fall in any of these countries is far more dangerous than witnesses had predicted,” said Abigail Grace, an Asia-centric research associate at the Center for New American Security, a committee of experts.
Syria is ‘prepared’ for refugees to return, according to Foreign Affairs Minister
Syria says it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country, devastated by a war of more than seven years.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Affairs Minister Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
"Currently, the situation on the street is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that the terrorists demolished to restore normality.
All conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that had to be abandoned due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and their maintenance are met.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the start of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people living in the country who need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime was grateful for any help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from the countries that financed the insurgency.
