Red tide update: concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general reduction in red tide concentrations in certain parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more dispersed proliferation conditions are being reported in the Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier areas, suggesting a lower concentration.
The proliferation of the red tide extends along approximately 200 km of coast, from the north of Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Spots can be found 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places, compared to last week's situation.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Average coastal or coastal concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, low-to-high concentrations in Hillsborough County, bottom or high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom-to-bottom concentrations in Charlotte County, and bottom-to-bottom concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory irritations continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation has been reported over the past week in northeastern Florida.
